 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Conditioning of roots\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider first the function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "f  = x -> (x-1)*(x-2);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "At the root $r=1$, we have $f'(r)=-1$. If the values of $f$ were perturbed at any point by noise of size, say, $0.05$, we can imagine finding the root of the function as though drawn with a thick line, whose edges we show here."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "interval = [0.8,1.2]\n",
    "\n",
    "using Plots\n",
    "plot(f,interval...,ribbon=0.03,legend=:none,aspect_ratio=1,\n",
    "    xlabel=\"x\",yaxis=(\"f(x)\",[-0.2,0.2],[0]),title=\"Well-conditioned root\")\n",
    "scatter!([1],[0])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The possible values for a perturbed root all lie within the interval where the ribbon intersects the $x$ axis. The width of that zone is about the same as the vertical distance between the lines.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "By contrast, consider the function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "f  = x -> (x-1)*(x-1.01);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now $f'(1)=-0.01$, and the graph of $f$ will be much shallower near $x=1$. Look at the effect this has on our thick rendering:"
   ]
  },
